For a classification problem with two classes we notice that the model with a maximum depth of 6 performs very good. For the problem with 4 classes we need a bigger depth (>=8) in order to have solid results.

Having more candidate feature response functions means that each node has better chance to pick the optimal response function. The same goes for the next hyperparameter which is the number of candidate thresholds per feature response function

By leaving the number of candidate feature response functions high, this hyperparameter does not have a big influence. However, if we lower the number of candidate response functions, this hyperparameter gives the ability to pick the best threshold for the limited candidates there are per node.
